Random forests for linguistic analysis

Jason Grafmiller

08 January, 2021

In this tutorial, we’ll go over the basics of how to use random forests, which are an extension of the decision tree methods we explored earlier.

Advantages of random forests:

  • Small n, big p: Random forests can handle small datasets with relatively large sets of predictors. This is a problem for other methods
  • Random forests are also robust against problems of collinearity due to their bagging and random variable selection procedures.
  • Random forests deal well with nonlinear effects and high-order interactions (though care should be taken, see Wright et al. 2016)
  • Very accurate: Random forests are typically much more accurate than single trees and even regression models

Disadvantages of random forests:

  • Cannot handle non-independence well. They don’t have a way of incorporating hierarchical data structures, i.e.“random” effects for speaker, text, etc.
  • Potentially long computing time (especially for variable imortance)
  • Do not provide traditional measures of effect size, direction, or significance

Setup

Before we get started, let’s load our basic libraries.

# install and load
library(tidyverse)

library(patchwork)

# for random forests
library(randomForest)
library(ranger)
library(party)
library(permimp)
library(edarf)

Datasets

For for classification trees we’ll use some of the datasets we looked at before.

# These two are big files so I have saved them as more efficient .rds files. These are not readable with other programs, e.g. Excel, but they take up less space and are quicker to load. 
gens <- readRDS("data_raw/brown_genitives.rds")
rels <- readRDS("data_raw/brown_relatives.rds")
# read from usual .csv file
english <- readRDS("data_raw/english_lexical_decision_Baayen.rds")

What are Random Forests?

Random forests are a powerful technique for predictive modeling and statistical inference. In a random forest we grow many trees trees as opposed to a single tree. To create the model, each tree makes a prediction and we say the tree “votes” for that outcome. For classification problems, the forest chooses the class having the most votes over all the trees in the forest. In case of regression, the forest takes the average of the predictions over all the different trees.

To understand why we might want to use random forests, it’s helpful to see the kinds of problems the method helps solve. One well-known problem with using single tree models is that the tree structure is highly sensitive to particulars of your dataset, because each split (after the initial one) depends on previous ones. Random Forests offer a solution to this problem.

We can illustrate this with a few random samples from the genitives dataset. We’ll start with the formula for genitive choice from previous tutorial. We’ll start with this.

gen_fmla2 <- Type ~ Possessor.Animacy.Bin + Final.Sibilant + 
  Possessor.Word.Count + Semantic.Relation.Bin + Possessor.Expression.Type + 
  Genre + Corpus + Possessum.Word.Count + PossessorTextFreq + 
  PossessumTextFreq + Prior.Genitive

Reset our factors.

factors <- c("Possessor.Animacy.Bin", "Final.Sibilant", "Semantic.Relation.Bin",
  "Possessor.Expression.Type", "Genre", "Corpus", "Prior.Genitive")
gens[factors] <- lapply(gens[factors], as.factor)
set.seed(43214) # set the random seed
library(partykit) # note that this will mask functions from party

Now will take several random subsamples of our dataset and fit trees to them.

ctree(gen_fmla2,
  data = gens[sample(1:nrow(gens), 200, replace = F),],
  control = ctree_control(mincriterion = .99, maxdepth = 4)) %>% 
  plot(gp = gpar(cex = .8)) 

ctree(gen_fmla2,
  data = gens[sample(1:nrow(gens), 200, replace = F),],
  control = ctree_control(mincriterion = .99, maxdepth = 4)) %>% 
  plot(gp = gpar(cex = .8)) 

ctree(gen_fmla2,
  data = gens[sample(1:nrow(gens), 200, replace = F),],
  control = ctree_control(mincriterion = .99, maxdepth = 4)) %>% 
  plot(gp = gpar(cex = .8))

Now, these are samll datasets (N = 200), and with larger samples we would likely get more convergence among the trees (try it your self!). But the larger point is that tree structures are highly volatile and sensitive to the particulars of the datasets they are trained on.

Random forests are one way of getting around this problem. They are one of a family of techniques that use ensemble methods to generate predictions. These methods rely on aggregating and summarising over lots of models rather than relying on one single model to derive predictions.

Bagging

One aspect of the random forests involves a process known as Bootstrap Aggregating, or bagging. Bagging is a technique used to reduce the variance of our predictions from individual trees by combining the result of many hundreds or thousands of trees trained on different sub-samples of the dataset. In this way, bagging is designed to improve the reliability and accuracy of a model as well as reduce variance and potential overfitting.

To obtain subsamples of the data, bagging relies on the principle of random sampling with replacement, or bootstrapping. The basic idea of bootstrapping goes as follows. Given a data set \(D_1\) with \(n\) observations, we create a new dataset \(D_2\) by randomly pulling out \(n\) observations from the original dataset \(D_1\), allowing that some of those observations may be copies. This is known as sampling “with replacement”, which simply means that each time we take a sample item from our set, we “replace” it with a copy in the original dataset. So the pool from which we draw our samples always stays the same, meaning that we could draw that same item again.

For example, suppose our dataset contained 26 observations, which we code with letters.

D1 <- letters
D1
 [1] "a" "b" "c" "d" "e" "f" "g" "h" "i" "j" "k" "l" "m" "n" "o" "p" "q" "r" "s"
[20] "t" "u" "v" "w" "x" "y" "z"

Now we take a sample of these observations by selecting a letter at random 26 times. This is our bootstrap sample.

D2 <- sample(D1, replace = T)
D2
 [1] "z" "s" "e" "j" "w" "t" "a" "j" "d" "v" "f" "v" "p" "s" "r" "g" "d" "u" "a"
[20] "e" "q" "d" "i" "l" "b" "g"

We can already see that some observations are repeated. This is the effect of sampling with replacement. We can see the proportion of non-repeated items…

# your mileage may vary
length(unique(D2))/length(D2)
[1] 0.6923077

Usually, about 1/3 of the observations from D1 are left out of D2. This is typical no matter how large the original dataset is.

One thing it’s important to remember is that because we’re moving into methods that rely on (pseudo) randomness, our results may vary across runs. This is why it’s important to set the random seed prior to running our models so that we can replicate our results again. All computer programs use pseudonrandom number algoritms to simulate randomness, and R is no different. We can take advantage of this to make sure we get the same results. We do this by setting the initial state of the random number generator to a predefined value with set.seed(). This can be any value.

set.seed(43214)

Which value you choose doesn’t matter in itself, but starting at that seed will always produce the same results.

Make sure to set this, and track it in your code so that you and anyone else can reproduce your analysis.

Random predictor sampling

A second aspect of random forests that makes them different from standard bagging methods is that when growing the individual trees, the method adds a second element of randomness in the selection of predictors that are included in each tree. When we have k input predictors, the random forest will randomly select a subset m < k out of the k predictors at each node, in each tree. The best split on these m predictors is used to split the node.

To sum up, instead of using a single tree, Random Forests grow many many decsion trees (a ‘forest’), each of which is grown on random subsamples of the data using randomly selected subsets of predictors. This results in a healthy mix of very diverse trees, which compensates for sparse values in the data while at the same time giving full consideration to possible effects of all predictors.

Random forests in R

There are three main packages for working with CART random forests: {randomForest}, and the newer {ranger} package, as well as the {party} package, which is a progenitor of {partykit}. We’ll first focus on the first two packages, since they use similar algorithms (), but run much faster than {party}.

Setting controls

In addition to the tunings for the individual trees, we need to specify two important (hyper)parameters for all random forest methods:

  • The number of input predictors randomly selected at each node of a given tree in the forest. We’ll call this \(m\)
  • The total number of trees to grow in the forest. We’ll call this \(N_{tree}\)

As a rule of thumb, Breiman (2001) recommends setting \(m\) equal to \(\sqrt{k}\) for a model with \(k\) predictors. The number of trees is something that is a bit harder to determine. Generally speaking, the smaller your dataset, and/or the larger the number of predictors, the more trees you should grow.

There are many more such hyperparameters we can set, and there are methods for exploring just what the optimal hyperparameter settings might be, but these can be very time consuming (prohibitively so with {party} forests), and are generally better suited to applications in which prediction is the primary goal. We will not go into this here, but see this post on tuning random forest hyperparameters for an illustration.

randomForest package

Let’s grow a forest with the {randomForest} package. Like rpart this uses by default the Gini index for splitting trees, following (???).

We’ll set the number of trees to grow at 2000, and set m to 3 (\(\sqrt{11}\) = 3.3166248)

length(all.vars(gen_fmla2)) 
[1] 12

We’ll also include the argument importance = TRUE, whoch will tell the model to provide a relative measure of how much each individual predictor adds to the predictive accuracy of the model. This will add to the computation time.

set.seed(1234)
# time the process
tic("Time to fit randomForest")
gen_for_randomForest <- randomForest(
  gen_fmla2, 
  data = gens, 
  ntree = 2000, 
  mtry = 3, 
  importance = TRUE)
toc()
Time to fit randomForest: 24.89 sec elapsed

So this didn’t take too long. Let’s look at the summary.

print(gen_for_randomForest)

Call:
 randomForest(formula = gen_fmla2, data = gens, ntree = 2000,      mtry = 3, importance = TRUE) 
               Type of random forest: classification
                     Number of trees: 2000
No. of variables tried at each split: 3

        OOB estimate of  error rate: 12.43%
Confusion matrix:
     of    s class.error
of 2923  279  0.08713304
s   369 1644  0.18330849

The printout gives us an estimate of accuracy based on the out-of-bag (OOB) error rates. “out-of-bag” refers to those observations that are left out of the randomly sampled “bag” of data used to train the trees For each tree, we test its predictions on these OOB observations and derive an error rate. The average error over all the trees is the estimated prediction error for the forest as a whole. In other words, the predictive accuracy is 1 - the OOB error rate, or 0.88.

We can obtain predictions with the predict() function, and we can measure the accuracy based on this.

gen_for_randomForest_preds <- predict(gen_for_randomForest)

which(gen_for_randomForest_preds == gens$Type) %>% 
  length(.)/nrow(gens)
[1] 0.875743

We can also get the predicted probabilities themselves, and measure the index of concordance C using somers2() in the {Hmisc} package.

gen_for_probs <- predict(gen_for_randomForest, type = "prob") %>% 
  as.data.frame
head(gen_for_probs)
Hmisc::somers2(gen_for_probs$s, 
  as.numeric(gens$Type) - 1)
           C          Dxy            n      Missing 
   0.9289602    0.8579204 5215.0000000    0.0000000

Very nice! Scores above .8 indicate good discrimination.

party package

Now we’ll try cforest() in the {party} package, since random forests have not been fully implemented in {partykit}. We detach {partykit} and load {party}. This is important to avoid conflicts between the two packages which share many of the same functions. This package relise on conditional inference methods similar to those in {partykit}.

detach("package:partykit", unload = TRUE)
library(party)

For {party}, we need to set the controls in the cforest_control() function. Once we’ve set our control parameters, we can fit our tree with cforest(). We will start with a simpler model, because this method is much slower than the others.

Predictor importance

Unlike single trees or regression models, reading partial effects off a random forest model is not easy because a single predictor can show up in many different (non-nested) trees with different co-varying predictors (and interactions). So random forests don’t give you direct effect size measures comparable to regression coefficients, nor to they conduct null hypothesis significance tests for your predictors, as with regression models.

But, random forests and ensemble methods make up for this shortcoming in being a great tool for model and predictor selection. Due to the random sampling and permutation processes, they are very good at determining the independent contributions of individual predictors to the model even when those predictors are highly correlated with one another (as is often the case). And since they rely on many, many trees, they can model non-linearities and complex ‘interactions’ quite naturally. All this results in us gaining much more information about how each predictor behaves.

To assess the contribution of each predictor, the random forest models compute a predictor importance score (also called “variable importance”). That’s what the importance arguments were for in the functions above.

The randomForest method uses decrease in predictive accuracy, and decrease in Gini index averaged over all the trees in the forest. These are measures of how much the accuracy or Gini index decreases when we that predictor is not present.

Let’s look at the Gini measure.

gen_for_randomForest$importance %>%
  as.data.frame %>% 
  rownames_to_column("Predictor") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(fct_reorder(Predictor, MeanDecreaseGini), MeanDecreaseGini)) +

The ranger package allows us to use a permutation importance measures. These have been shown to be less biased than other measures (see Strobl et al. 2009). Wright et al. (???) describe how permutation variable importance works as follows.

To evaluate predictor importance, a tree is grown in the first step, and the prediction accuracy in the OOB observations is calculated. In the second step, any association between the variable of interest \(x_i\) and the outcome is broken by permuting the values of all individuals for \(x_i\), and the prediction accuracy is computed again. The difference between the two accuracy values is the permutation importance for \(x_i\) from a single tree. The average of all tree importance values in a random forest then gives the random forest permutation importance of this variable. The procedure is repeated for all predictors of interest.

In other words, we…

  1. Grow a tree predicting a response from a set of predictors.
  2. Take one predictor and randomly shuffle the values of that predictor to break the association between the response and predictor
  3. Calculate the difference in model accuracy before and after shuffling.
  4. Repeat for all trees and all predictors in the forest

If the predictor does not have a meaningful relationship with the response, shuffling its values should produce very little change in model accuracy. On the other hand, if the predictor was strongly associated with the response, permutation should create a large drop in accuracy. We do this for every predictor in the model, and rank them according to their importance.

Permutation variable importance covers the individual impact of each predictor in the random forest model, including its impact in interactions (which is much harder to assess in regression models).

gen_ranger_varimp <- importance(gen_ranger_perm) %>% 
  as.data.frame %>% 
  rename(varimp = ".") %>% 
  mutate(pred = rownames(.) %>% factor)

ggplot(gen_ranger_varimp, aes(fct_reorder(pred, varimp), varimp)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "", y = "permutation predictor importance\n(mean decrease in accuracy)") +
  coord_flip()

The party package uses permutation importance measures as well, and it offers two measures, the decrease in prediction accuracy (varimp()) and the decrease in C (varimpAUC()). The latter has been argued to be a more reliable measure (see ???), so this is the one I recommend.

The only drawback is that these are also very time consuming, like everything in {party}. Fortunately, the {permimp} package was developed to speed things along, and to address issues with earlier methods (???). We just use the permimp() function on our model object.

# track the time it takes to run
tic()
gen_party1_varimp <- permimp(
  gen_party1,
  AUC = TRUE, # use the AUC (concordance index) rather than accuracy
  progressBar = FALSE # don't print a progress bar here
  )
toc()

Once we have our variable importance object, we can plot the results. First we convert it to a data.frame object which we can then use with ggplot().

gen_party1_varimp_df <- gen_party1_varimp$values %>% 
  as.data.frame %>% 
  rename(varimp = ".") %>% 
  mutate(pred = rownames(.) %>% factor)

p1 <- gen_party1_varimp_df %>% 
  ggplot(aes(fct_reorder(pred, varimp), varimp)) +
  geom_segment(aes(xend = pred, yend = 0)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  labs(x = "", y = "Permutation predictor importance\n(mean decrease in AUC)") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "red") +
  coord_flip() +
  ggtitle("Permutation importance for party forest")
p1

By chance, the random reordering of values sometimes results in a configuration that affords a slightly better model. This may arise when the values of an irrelevant predictor are reshuffled. In other words, the random reshuffling created a new version of the predictor that is actually more strongly associated with the outcome than the original predictor. This has the effect of creating a negative variable importance score.

By mirroring the minimal score to the right of zero, we obtain an interval that characterizes irrelevant predictors. Variables can be considered informative and important if their variable importance value lies above (to the right) this region (???). In some cases, this may include all predictors.

It’s important to remember that these variable importance scores should only be interpreted relative to each other as a ranking of the model’s predictors. The absolute values of the scores should not be interpreted or compared across studies (see Strobl et al. 2009:336).

Since the forest are random, they should also be verified by fitting multiple models with different random seeds and ntree numbers.

Finally, with party forests there is the option conditional = TRUE, which computes the conditional permutation importance of each predictor, which represents the effect of a predictor in both main effects and interactions. This is especially usefull for investigating the effects of potentially correlated and/or interacting predictors. See (???) for details.

Conditional importances also take a bit longer to run.

# track the time it takes to run
tic()
gen_party1_varimp_cond <- permimp(
  gen_party1,
  AUC = TRUE, # use the AUC (concordance index) rather than accuracy
  progressBar = FALSE, # don't print a progress bar here,
  conditional = TRUE
  )
toc()
gen_party1_varimp_cond_df <- gen_party1_varimp_cond$values %>% 
  as.data.frame %>% 
  rename(varimp = ".") %>% 
  mutate(pred = rownames(.) %>% factor)

p2 <- gen_party1_varimp_cond_df %>% 
  ggplot(aes(fct_reorder(pred, varimp), varimp)) +
  geom_segment(aes(xend = pred, yend = 0)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  labs(x = "", y = "Permutation predictor importance\n(mean decrease in AUC)") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "red") +
  coord_flip() +
  ggtitle("Conditional permutation importance for party forest")
p2

As you can see, this doesn’t always make much difference, but it can.

Partial dependencies

As I mentioned above, reading effects of individual predictors off a random forest model is not easy because a forest—as the name implies—can contain many hundreds or even thousands of potentially very different trees. There is therefore no method for computing p-values for individual predictors effects or their interactions.

That said, we can examine the effects of an individual predictor (and its relation to other predictors), we plot the partial dependence of the probability of the response on that predictor or predictors, while averaging over the values of the other predictors. This method is similar in spirit to partial effects plots derived from regression models, though these should not be interpreted as significance tests.

There is a nice package edarf that can quickly calculate partial dependence plots with a convernient partial_dependence() function.

library(edarf)

There is a more recent package {pdp} which can be used for calculating partial dependencies, but it is very time consuming, even for ranger models. For party models I’ve had processes run for +10 hours before cancelling.

Categorical responses

Let’s estimate the partial dependency of genitive constructions on Genre in the randomForest model.

set.seed(1234)
pd_ranFor1 <- partial_dependence(
  gen_for_randomForest, 
  vars = 'Genre', 
  n = c(5, 100), 
  data = gens)
pd_ranFor1

Note the argument n = c(5, 20). This controls how the function calculates the partial dependencies. The first element specifies the levels of the predictor at which to measure the probabilities of the response classes. The second element gives the number of rows of the other predictors to sample when calcuating their averages. Generally, for categorical predictors we want to specify the first argument as simply the number of levels in that predictor.

The package has its own plot function plot_pd(), but I’ve found it to be a bit buggy, and so I perfer to do things my own way.

pd_ranFor1 %>% 
  as.data.frame %>% 
  reshape2::melt(id.vars = "Genre") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Genre, 
             y = value, 
             color = variable, 
             group = variable)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = .5, linetype = 2) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "", y = "probability of response")

We can plot interactions easily too. Let’s look at how the effect of Possessor animacy changes across genres.

set.seed(1234)
pd_ranFor2 <- partial_dependence(gen_for_randomForest, 
  vars = c('Genre', 'Possessor.Animacy.Bin'), 
  n = c(10, 100), # we set the first number to 2 animacy levels x 5 genres = 10
  data = gens,
  interaction = TRUE)
pd_ranFor2
pd_ranFor2 %>% 
  as.data.frame %>% 
  reshape2::melt(id.vars = c("Genre", "Possessor.Animacy.Bin")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Genre, 
             y = value, 
             color = variable, 
             group = variable)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = .5, linetype = 2) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~ Possessor.Animacy.Bin, ncol = 2) +
  labs(x = "", y = "probability of response") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 0, vjust = 0))

Maybe not the best plot, but we get the picture that the animacy effect is substantially weakened in Press texts compared to the other genres.

# another way of looking at it where we only plot the probability of one response
pd_ranFor2 %>% 
  as.data.frame %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Genre, y = s, 
             color = Possessor.Animacy.Bin, 
             group = Possessor.Animacy.Bin)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = .5, linetype = 2) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "", y = "probability of s-genitive") +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Plotting effects of continuous predictors is a bit trickier, but it’s all a matter of setting the desired values. For example, let’s look at the influence of relative clause length on the choice of relativizer.

hist(rels$RCLn)

Most of the data points (90%) fall below 12, so we can focus on the region of the data where the RC is below this

quantile(rels$RCLn, .9)
90% 
 15

We’ll increase the number of levels and samples to compute the probabilities over. From the plot we can see that the longer the RC gets, the more likely an overt relativizer becomes.

set.seed(1234)
partial_dependence(rel_randomForest, 
  vars = "RCLn", 
  n = c(40, 100),
  data = rels,
  interaction = FALSE) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>%
  subset(RCLn <= 12) %>% 
  reshape2::melt(id.vars = "RCLn") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = RCLn, 
             y = value, # include only the 
             color = variable, 
             group = variable)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = .5, linetype = 2) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point()+
  labs(x = "", y = "probability of response")

We can do the same with all the “main effects” simultaneously with a little knowledge of loops. First we create a vector of all the predictors in our formula (we’ll just focus on a subset here)

f <- rel ~ time2 + RCLn + variety + antLN
# leave out the response
vars <- all.vars(f)[-1]

Now we define a function that will calculate the partial dependence for a given predictor and generate a ggplot object for it. For the n argument in partial_dependence(), we’ll have the function find the appropriate number of levels for factor predictors, or use 10 if the predictor is numeric.

pd.func <- function(x) {
  nlevs <- ifelse(is.factor(rels[, x]), nlevels(rels[, x]), 20)
  set.seed(1234)
  p <- partial_dependence(rel_randomForest, 
    vars = x, n = c(nlevs, 100), data = rels) %>% 
    reshape2::melt(id.vars = x) %>% 
    ggplot(aes_string(x = x, y = 'value', group = 'variable')) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = .5, linetype = 'dashed') +
    geom_line(aes(color = variable)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = variable)) +
    labs(x = x, y = 'predicted probability')
  return(p)
}

Next we just loop through the list of predictors and apply our function using llply(). This function takes a vector of items, applies a function, and returns the outputs of the function in a list.

# loop through predictors and get the partial dependency plots
partials <- vector("list")
for (i in 1:length(vars)){
  partials[[i]] <- pd.func(vars[i])
}
names(partials) <- vars

Finally, we’ll arrange these all in a single plot grid.

wrap_plots(partials, ncol = 2)

Alternatively, you could plot each predictor individually with partials[[i]] where i is either the name of the predictor or the number of its place in the list.

Continuous responses

Continuous responses can be included just as easily.

set.seed(1234)
partial_dependence(lexdec_randomForest, 
  vars = "WrittenFrequency", 
  n = c(20, 50),
  data = english,
  interaction = FALSE) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = WrittenFrequency, 
             y = RTlexdec)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  annotate(geom = "segment", # we'll add a line for the mean 
           x = min(english$WrittenFrequency),
           xend = max(english$WrittenFrequency),
           y = mean(english$RTlexdec), 
           yend = mean(english$RTlexdec), linetype = 2) +
  labs(x = "", y = "predicted response time latency")

Summary

Advantages of random forests:

  • Small n, big p: Random forests can handle small datasets with relatively large sets of predictors. This is a problem for other methods
  • Random forests are also robust against problems of collinearity due to their bagging and random variable selection procedures.
  • Random forests deal well with nonlinear effects and high-order interactions (though care should be taken, see Wright et al. 2016)
  • Very accurate: Random forests are typically much more accurate than single trees and even regression models

Disadvantages of random forests:

  • Cannot handle non-independence well. They don’t have a way of incorporating hierarchical data structures, i.e.“random” effects for speaker, text, etc.
  • Potentially long computing time (especially for variable imortance)
  • Do not provide traditional measures of effect size, direction, or significance
